<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-437-620  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 437 620.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  May 7 1990 n589 p26(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Congress high on East Bloc potential. (favors relaxation of exportcontrols)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robinson, Brian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Much of the US Senate sees the changes in the politicalinfrastructure of Central and Eastern Europe as opening newavenues for US trade and investment, although a few members areconcerned about possible threats to US security in theliberalization of export controls.andP;  A House subcommittee recentlypassed a revised and liberalized version of the ExportAdministration Act, the legislation governing export oftechnological goods and services.andP;  Sen John Heinz (R-PA) has senta five-point strategy plan to Pres Bush listing suggested changesto US export controls for Poland, Hungary, Czechoslovakia and EastGermany that includes moving the four countries to theCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export Controls' (COCOM)'free-world' designation, decontrolling them to the same level asChina, giving favorable consideration to liberalizing exports tothe four beyond that of China, moving the Soviet Union to theChinese control level without accompanying decontrol, andannouncing that the US National Security Council has been orderedto prepare a new 'control list' for COCOM.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International TradeExportUnited States. Congress. HouseEastern Europe.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>